Exploring a dataframe.

This is the cheatsheet for answering one question — what does this dataframe actually contain?

Count gives you the number of rows. Note that count is an action, so it triggers a job.

Columns gives you the column names as a Python list. D-types gives you name-and-type-string tuples. Schema gives you the full struct-type object, and print-schema pretty-prints it.

Describe gives you the count, mean, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum for the numeric columns. And summary gives you all of that, plus the quartiles.

Finally, show prints the actual rows. Pass truncate equals false when you want to see the full content of each cell.

One thing to keep in mind. Columns, d-types, and schema are cheap metadata reads. But count, describe, summary, and show are actions — each one actually runs a job on the cluster.
